What is the direct age-standardization

Mortality is the death number at a specified population presented in ‰ format. For a particular population, we get the mortality by \[ \frac{text{number of death}}{text{particular population}}*1000 \] We call it Crud Mortality Rate(CMR).

When we need to compare the mortality of two populations, can we compare the CRD of two population directly? We won’t get the right result if these two population have two different population pyramids. Because age is the confounding factor that affect the death rate, so for a population with more older age people, its death rate would be higher than if its age structure is the same as the other population. To get rid of the influnce of the confounding factor of age, we need to standardize the age first and then compare their mortality. This process is called age-standardization. There are two ways to standardize the age: direct age-standardization and indirect age-standardization. Here is an example of direct age-standardization. The following are the population pyramids for Canada and India in the year of 2019:

Based on the data from worldpopulationreview website, Canda’s death rate was 7.89, and India’s death rate was 6.75 in the year of 2019. Does this mean the death rate of india is lower than that of Canada? Not really; because compare the populaiton pyramids of the two countries, we can see that India has much less older aged people (see the percent of people aged above 70 in the pyramids) We need to use age-standardization to get the more objective comparison result. Here is what we will do.

Let’s call Canada’s death rate Mortality_Canada_CRD, which is 7.89, and India’s death rate Mortality_India_CRD, which is 6.75.

Firstly, we’ll need to get the dearth rate by age group for both countries: Canada and India. Then we use the age structure of Canada and the death rate by age group of India to calculate the total death for each age group. Then we sum the death total of each age group to get the total death. This number should be the total death of Canada if it has the same death age by age group as India has. Use the total divided by the total of Canada’s population, we’ll call this number Standard Rate Death(SRD). Next, we can compare the
